\section*{Abstract} 
Previous meta-analyses of phenology responses to climate change have focused largely on temperature as a driver of observed shifts. Yet climate change also affects soil moisture, which is limiting to many biological responses. Here we synthesize microclimate and phenology data from climate change experiments in temperate systems---both forests and grasslands---to quantify how soil moisture interacts with temperature to affect plant phenology. We find that phenology (budburst, leafout and flowering) delays in drier soils, with the largest delays seen in budburst.  
