\par We found that both higher soil moisture and higher temperatures advance phenology, meaning two common effects of warming experiments---soil drying and warming---have contrasting effects on phenology (Fig. \ref{fig:bblofl}, Table S2). Soil drying delays phenology and warming temperatures advance phenology. For budburst, wetter soils and warmer temperatures alone advanced phenology by \Sexpr{soileff.bbcent} (\Sexpr{soileff.bbcent.lci},\Sexpr{soileff.bbcent.uci}) days per SD of soil moisture  (or \Sexpr{soileff.bb/10} days per 10 percent increase in volumetric water content) and \Sexpr{tempeff.bbcent} (\Sexpr{tempeff.bbcent.lci},\Sexpr{tempeff.bbcent.uci}) days per SD of temperature (or \Sexpr{tempeff.bb} per degree Celsius). We did not find evidence of strong interactive effects of soil moisture and temperature on phenology: together, wetter and warmer conditions delayed budburst only a small amount (interaction effect of \Sexpr{inteff.bbcent} [\Sexpr{inteff.bbcent.lci}-\Sexpr{inteff.bbcent.uci}] days per SD). % or \Sexpr{inteff.bb}in natural units

\par The magnitude of soil moisture effects varied across phenophases, with effects on budburst (\Sexpr{soileff.bbcent} [\Sexpr{soileff.bbcent.lci},\Sexpr{soileff.bbcent.uci}] days per SD increase in soil moisture) being stronger than those on leafout (\Sexpr{soileff.locent} [\Sexpr{soileff.locent.lci},\Sexpr{soileff.locent.uci}] per SD increase in soil moisture) and flowering (\Sexpr{soileff.flcent} [\Sexpr{soileff.flcent.lci},\Sexpr{soileff.flcent.uci}] per SD increase in moisture). Similar to budburst, temperature effects were stronger than soil moisture for leafout (for which the temperature effect was \Sexpr{tempeff.locent} [\Sexpr{tempeff.locent.lci},\Sexpr{tempeff.locent.uci}] days per SD increase in temperature) and flowering (for which it was \Sexpr{tempeff.flcent} [\Sexpr{tempeff.flcent.lci},\Sexpr{tempeff.flcent.uci}] per SD increase in temperature), across all species (Fig. \ref{fig:bblofl}). Estimates of interactions between soil moisture and temperature on phenology also varied by phenophase, with weakly positive or no interactive effects estimated for leafout (\Sexpr{inteff.locent}) [\Sexpr{inteff.locent.lci},\Sexpr{inteff.locent.uci}] and budburst (\Sexpr{inteff.bbcent} [\Sexpr{inteff.bbcent.lci},\Sexpr{inteff.bbcent.uci}]) and a stronger but negative interaction for flowering (\Sexpr{inteff.flcent} [\Sexpr{inteff.flcent.lci},\Sexpr{inteff.flcent.uci}]). This negative interaction implies that there may be synergistic effects of soil moisture and temperature (both of which also have negative estimated effects on flowering), resulting in flowering that advances even more strongly than would be expected by simply adding together the  estimated effects of temperature and  moisture each acting alone. %emwDec15 --  nice stuff here. It's hard to explain interactions well and you did it here, so -- well done!

